Did people at the end of the 19th century and the very early 20th century just intentionally start fires that destroyed major parts of many cities in the USA for some reason? Because they had to be rebuilt with better infrastructure anyways or to get insurance money or something?

I assume firefighting and fireproofing technology got a lot better really quickly during WW1 but it seems there were a few decades where a ton of cities had a "Great Fire of X" which destroyed 30% of the buildings and then they proceeded to rebuild entire neighborhoods afterwards

It just keeps popping up as a pattern. Some settlement is created in the start of the 19th century, starts growing rapidly in the following decades, then one night in 1901 a freak fire starts and consumes half of the town, which is then rapidly rebuilt. Has to be organized arson.

Just got caught up on the Mike Israel PhD dissertation fiasco and it 100% proves my theory that all sociopaths are retarde. He genuinely thought he could have Machiavellied his way out of the situation but he's genuinely dumb as rocks and just made the entire thing 10 times worse

The worst part is if he had ANY semblance of humility he could have just said "yeah I admit it is a bad work, it's a niche closed-off field, we all know each other and it's obvious no one was going to read it", his PhD is 100% at worst SLIGHTLY below average for exercise science.

If you just start going through other random exercise "science" PhD works I guarantee you're going to find way worse stuff. But he just had to start playing 4D chess (in reality - 1D chess) and lying through his teeth and scamming his friends for zero reason completely ineptly.

The most bizarre part is that like 6 years ago he was legitimately very well respected and I remember reading some bodybuilding periodization stuff from him that was very sensible and useful posted on reddit, no idea how he ended up like this

Worst part is at one point he apparently tried to throw his academic advisor/professor under the bus by trying to bullshit about it being a collaborative work, not choosing the PhD topic himself, etc. It's obviously all sorta true, but brazenly bad manners in academic environment

And I'm pretty sure he used to call his PhD advisor his mentor too, just zero regard for friendship, throwing anyone possible under the bus to pass as much blame as possible to others while acting nonchalant and above it all and pretending he doesn't care. Sociopathy=retardation.
